#: ../../../interactive.rst:4
msgid "Interactive use"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:6
msgid ""
"Fish prides itself on being really nice to use interactively. That's down to "
"a few features we'll explain in the next few sections."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:8
msgid ""
"Fish is used by giving commands in the fish language, see :ref:`The Fish "
"Language <language>` for information on that."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:11
msgid "Help"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:13
msgid ""
"Fish has an extensive help system. Use the :doc:`help <cmds/help>` command "
"to obtain help on a specific subject or command. For instance, writing "
"``help syntax`` displays the :ref:`syntax section <syntax>` of this "
"documentation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:15
msgid ""
"Fish also has man pages for its commands, and translates the help pages to "
"man pages. For example, ``man set`` will show the documentation for ``set`` "
"as a man page."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:17
msgid ""
"Help on a specific builtin can also be obtained with the ``-h`` parameter. "
"For instance, to obtain help on the :doc:`fg <cmds/fg>` builtin, either type "
"``fg -h`` or ``help fg``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:19
msgid ""
"The main page can be viewed via ``help index`` (or just ``help``) or ``man "
"fish-doc``. The tutorial can be viewed with ``help tutorial`` or ``man fish-"
"tutorial``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:24
msgid "Autosuggestions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:26
msgid ""
"fish suggests commands as you type, based on :ref:`command history <history-"
"search>`, completions, and valid file paths. As you type commands, you will "
"see a suggestion offered after the cursor, in a muted gray color (which can "
"be changed with the ``fish_color_autosuggestion`` variable)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:28
msgid ""
"To accept the autosuggestion (replacing the command line contents), press :"
"kbd:`→` or :kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`F`. To accept the first suggested "
"word, press :kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`→` or :kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`F`. If the "
"autosuggestion is not what you want, just ignore it: it won't execute unless "
"you accept it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:30
msgid ""
"Autosuggestions are a powerful way to quickly summon frequently entered "
"commands, by typing the first few characters. They are also an efficient "
"technique for navigating through directory hierarchies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:32
msgid ""
"If you don't like autosuggestions, you can disable them by setting "
"``$fish_autosuggestion_enabled`` to 0::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:34
msgid "set -g fish_autosuggestion_enabled 0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:39
msgid "Tab Completion"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:41
msgid ""
"Tab completion is a time saving feature of any modern shell. When you type :"
"kbd:`Tab`, fish tries to guess the rest of the word under the cursor. If it "
"finds just one possibility, it inserts it. If it finds more, it inserts the "
"longest unambiguous part and then opens a menu (the \"pager\") that you can "
"navigate to find what you're looking for."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:43
msgid ""
"The pager can be navigated with the arrow keys, :kbd:`Page Up` / :kbd:`Page "
"Down`, :kbd:`Tab` or :kbd:`Shift`\\ +\\ :kbd:`Tab`. Pressing :kbd:"
"`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`S` (the ``pager-toggle-search`` binding - :kbd:`/` in "
"vi-mode) opens up a search menu that you can use to filter the list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:45
msgid ""
"Fish provides some general purpose completions, like for commands, variable "
"names, usernames or files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:47
msgid ""
"It also provides a large number of program specific scripted completions. "
"Most of these completions are simple options like the ``-l`` option for "
"``ls``, but a lot are more advanced. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:49
msgid "``man`` and ``whatis`` show the installed manual pages as completions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:51
msgid ""
"``make`` uses targets in the Makefile in the current directory as "
"completions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:53
msgid "``mount`` uses mount points specified in fstab as completions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:55
msgid "``apt``, ``rpm`` and ``yum`` show installed or installable packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:57
msgid ""
"You can also write your own completions or install some you got from someone "
"else. For that, see :ref:`Writing your own completions <completion-own>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:59
msgid ""
"Completion scripts are loaded on demand, just like :ref:`functions are "
"<syntax-function-autoloading>`. The difference is the "
"``$fish_complete_path`` :ref:`list <variables-lists>` is used instead of "
"``$fish_function_path``. Typically you can drop new completions in ~/.config/"
"fish/completions/name-of-command.fish and fish will find them automatically."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:64
msgid "Syntax highlighting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:66
msgid ""
"Fish interprets the command line as it is typed and uses syntax highlighting "
"to provide feedback. The most important feedback is the detection of "
"potential errors. By default, errors are marked red."
msgstr ""

