#: ../../../interactive.rst:183
msgid "Abbreviations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:185
msgid ""
"To avoid needless typing, a frequently-run command like ``git checkout`` can "
"be abbreviated to ``gco`` using the :doc:`abbr <cmds/abbr>` command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:189
msgid "abbr -a gco git checkout"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:191
msgid ""
"After entering ``gco`` and pressing :kbd:`Space` or :kbd:`Enter`, a ``gco`` "
"in command position will turn into ``git checkout`` in the command line. If "
"you want to use a literal ``gco`` sometimes, use :kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:"
"`Space` [#]_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:193
msgid ""
"This is a lot more powerful, for example you can make going up a number of "
"directories easier with this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:195
msgid ""
"function multicd\n"
"    echo cd (string repeat -n (math (string length -- $argv[1]) - 1) ../)\n"
"end\n"
"abbr --add dotdot --regex '^\\.\\.+$' --function multicd"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:200
msgid ""
"Now, ``..`` transforms to ``cd ../``, while ``...`` turns into ``cd ../../`` "
"and ``....`` expands to ``cd ../../../``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:202
msgid ""
"The advantage over aliases is that you can see the actual command before "
"using it, add to it or change it, and the actual command will be stored in "
"history."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:204
msgid ""
"Any binding that executes the ``expand-abbr`` or ``execute`` :doc:`bind "
"function <cmds/bind>` will expand abbreviations. By default :kbd:`Control`\\ "
"+\\ :kbd:`Space` is bound to just inserting a space."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:209
msgid "Programmable title"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:211
msgid ""
"When using most virtual terminals, it is possible to set the message "
"displayed in the titlebar of the terminal window. This can be done "
"automatically in fish by defining the :doc:`fish_title <cmds/fish_title>` "
"function. The :doc:`fish_title <cmds/fish_title>` function is executed "
"before and after a new command is executed or put into the foreground and "
"the output is used as a titlebar message. The :doc:`status current-command "
"<cmds/status>` builtin will always return the name of the job to be put into "
"the foreground (or ``fish`` if control is returning to the shell) when the :"
"doc:`fish_prompt <cmds/fish_prompt>` function is called. The first argument "
"to fish_title will contain the most recently executed foreground command as "
"a string."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:213
msgid ""
"The default fish title shows the hostname if connected via ssh, the "
"currently running command (unless it is fish) and the current working "
"directory. All of this is shortened to not make the tab too wide."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:215 ../../../interactive.rst:637
msgid "Examples:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:217
msgid "To show the last command and working directory in the title::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:219
msgid ""
"function fish_title\n"
"    # `prompt_pwd` shortens the title. This helps prevent tabs from becoming "
"very wide.\n"
"    echo $argv[1] (prompt_pwd)\n"
"    pwd\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:228
msgid "Programmable prompt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:230
msgid ""
"When it is fish's turn to ask for input (like after it started or the "
"command ended), it will show a prompt. It does this by running the :doc:"
"`fish_prompt <cmds/fish_prompt>` and :doc:`fish_right_prompt <cmds/"
"fish_right_prompt>` functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:232
msgid ""
"The output of the former is displayed on the left and the latter's output on "
"the right side of the terminal. The output of :doc:`fish_mode_prompt <cmds/"
"fish_mode_prompt>` will be prepended on the left, though the default "
"function only does this when in :ref:`vi-mode <vi-mode>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:237
msgid "Configurable greeting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:239
msgid ""
"When it is started interactively, fish tries to run the :doc:`fish_greeting "
"<cmds/fish_greeting>` function. The default fish_greeting prints a simple "
"greeting. You can change its text by changing the ``$fish_greeting`` "
"variable, for instance using a :ref:`universal variable <variables-"
"universal>`::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:241
msgid "set -U fish_greeting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:243
msgid ""
"or you can set it :ref:`globally <variables-scope>` in :ref:`config.fish "
"<configuration>`::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:245
msgid "set -g fish_greeting 'Hey, stranger!'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:247
msgid "or you can script it by changing the function::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:249
msgid ""
"function fish_greeting\n"
"    random choice \"Hello!\" \"Hi\" \"G'day\" \"Howdy\"\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:253
msgid ""
"save this in config.fish or :ref:`a function file <syntax-function-"
"autoloading>`. You can also use :doc:`funced <cmds/funced>` and :doc:"
"`funcsave <cmds/funcsave>` to edit it easily."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:258
msgid "Private mode"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:260
msgid ""
"If ``$fish_private_mode`` is set to a non-empty value, commands will not be "
"written to the history file on disk."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:262
msgid ""
"You can also launch with ``fish --private`` (or ``fish -P`` for short). This "
"both hides old history and prevents writing history to disk. This is useful "
"to avoid leaking personal information (e.g. for screencasts) or when dealing "
"with sensitive information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:264
msgid ""
"You can query the variable ``fish_private_mode`` (``if test -n "
"\"$fish_private_mode\" ...``) if you would like to respect the user's wish "
"for privacy and alter the behavior of your own fish scripts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:269
msgid "Command line editor"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:271
msgid ""
"The fish editor features copy and paste, a :ref:`searchable history <history-"
"search>` and many editor functions that can be bound to special keyboard "
"shortcuts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:273
msgid ""
"Like bash and other shells, fish includes two sets of keyboard shortcuts (or "
"key bindings): one inspired by the Emacs text editor, and one by the Vi text "
"editor. The default editing mode is Emacs. You can switch to Vi mode by "
"running :doc:`fish_vi_key_bindings <cmds/fish_vi_key_bindings>` and switch "
"back with :doc:`fish_default_key_bindings <cmds/fish_default_key_bindings>`. "
"You can also make your own key bindings by creating a function and setting "
"the ``fish_key_bindings`` variable to its name. For example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:276
msgid ""
"function fish_hybrid_key_bindings --description \\\n"
"\"Vi-style bindings that inherit emacs-style bindings in all modes\"\n"
"    for mode in default insert visual\n"
"        fish_default_key_bindings -M $mode\n"
"    end\n"
"    fish_vi_key_bindings --no-erase\n"
"end\n"
"set -g fish_key_bindings fish_hybrid_key_bindings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:285
msgid ""
"While the key bindings included with fish include many of the shortcuts "
"popular from the respective text editors, they are not a complete "
"implementation. They include a shortcut to open the current command line in "
"your preferred editor (:kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`E` by default) if you need the "
"full power of your editor."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:290
msgid "Shared bindings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:292
msgid ""
"Some bindings are common across Emacs and Vi mode, because they aren't text "
"editing bindings, or because what Vi/Vim does for a particular key doesn't "
"make sense for a shell."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:294
msgid ""
":kbd:`Tab` :ref:`completes <tab-completion>` the current token. :kbd:"
"`Shift`\\ +\\ :kbd:`Tab` completes the current token and starts the pager's "
"search mode. :kbd:`Tab` is the same as :kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`I`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:296
msgid ""
":kbd:`←` (Left) and :kbd:`→` (Right) move the cursor left or right by one "
"character. If the cursor is already at the end of the line, and an "
"autosuggestion is available, :kbd:`→` accepts the autosuggestion."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:298
msgid ""
":kbd:`Enter` executes the current commandline or inserts a newline if it's "
"not complete yet (e.g. a ``)`` or ``end`` is missing)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:300
msgid ":kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`Enter` inserts a newline at the cursor position."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:302
msgid ""
":kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`←` and :kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`→` move the cursor one "
"word left or right (to the next space or punctuation mark), or moves forward/"
"backward in the directory history if the command line is empty. If the "
"cursor is already at the end of the line, and an autosuggestion is "
"available, :kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`→` (or :kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`F`) accepts "
"the first word in the suggestion."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:304
msgid ""
":kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`←` and :kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`→` move the "
"cursor one word left or right. These accept one word of the autosuggestion - "
"the part they'd move over."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:306
msgid ""
":kbd:`Shift`\\ +\\ :kbd:`←` and :kbd:`Shift`\\ +\\ :kbd:`→` move the cursor "
"one word left or right, without stopping on punctuation. These accept one "
"big word of the autosuggestion."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:308
msgid ""
":kbd:`↑` (Up) and :kbd:`↓` (Down) (or :kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`P` and :kbd:"
"`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`N` for emacs aficionados) search the command history "
"for the previous/next command containing the string that was specified on "
"the commandline before the search was started. If the commandline was empty "
"when the search started, all commands match. See the :ref:`history <history-"
"search>` section for more information on history searching."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:310
msgid ""
":kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`↑` and :kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`↓` search the command "
"history for the previous/next token containing the token under the cursor "
"before the search was started. If the commandline was not on a token when "
"the search started, all tokens match. See the :ref:`history <history-"
"search>` section for more information on history searching."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:312
msgid ""
":kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`C` interrupt/kill whatever is running (SIGINT)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:314
msgid ""
":kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`D` delete one character to the right of the "
"cursor. If the command line is empty, :kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`D` will "
"exit fish."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:316
msgid ""
":kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`U` removes contents from the beginning of line to "
"the cursor (moving it to the :ref:`killring <killring>`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:318
msgid ":kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`L` clears and repaints the screen."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:320
msgid ""
":kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`W` removes the previous path component "
"(everything up to the previous \"/\", \":\" or \"@\") (moving it to the :ref:"
"`killring`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:322
msgid ""
":kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`X` copies the current buffer to the system's "
"clipboard, :kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`V` inserts the clipboard contents. "
"(see :doc:`fish_clipboard_copy <cmds/fish_clipboard_copy>` and :doc:"
"`fish_clipboard_paste <cmds/fish_clipboard_paste>`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:324
msgid ":kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`D` moves the next word to the :ref:`killring`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:326
msgid ""
":kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`H` (or :kbd:`F1`) shows the manual page for the "
"current command, if one exists."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:328
msgid ""
":kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`L` lists the contents of the current directory, "
"unless the cursor is over a directory argument, in which case the contents "
"of that directory will be listed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:330
msgid ":kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`O` opens the file at the cursor in a pager."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:332
msgid ""
":kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`P` adds the string ``&| less;`` to the end of the job "
"under the cursor. The result is that the output of the command will be paged."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:334
msgid ""
":kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`W` prints a short description of the command under "
"the cursor."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:336
msgid ""
":kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`E` edit the current command line in an external "
"editor. The editor is chosen from the first available of the ``$VISUAL`` or "
"``$EDITOR`` variables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:338
msgid ":kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`V` Same as :kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`E`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:340
msgid ""
":kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`S` Prepends ``sudo`` to the current commandline. If "
"the commandline is empty, prepend ``sudo`` to the last commandline."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:342
msgid ""
":kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`Space` Inserts a space without expanding an :ref:"
"`abbreviation <abbreviations>`. For vi-mode this only applies to insert-mode."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:347
msgid "Emacs mode commands"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:349
msgid ""
"To enable emacs mode, use :doc:`fish_default_key_bindings <cmds/"
"fish_default_key_bindings>`. This is also the default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:351
msgid ""
":kbd:`Home` or :kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`A` moves the cursor to the "
"beginning of the line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:353
msgid ""
":kbd:`End` or :kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`E` moves to the end of line. If the "
"cursor is already at the end of the line, and an autosuggestion is "
"available, :kbd:`End` or :kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`E` accepts the "
"autosuggestion."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:355
msgid ""
":kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`B`, :kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`F` move the cursor "
"one character left or right or accept the autosuggestion just like the :kbd:"
"`←` (Left) and :kbd:`→` (Right) shared bindings (which are available as "
"well)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:357
msgid ""
":kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`N`, :kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`P` move the cursor "
"up/down or through history, like the up and down arrow shared bindings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:359
msgid ""
":kbd:`Delete` or :kbd:`Backspace` removes one character forwards or "
"backwards respectively. This also goes for :kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`H`, "
"which is indistinguishable from backspace."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:361
msgid ":kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`Backspace` removes one word backwards."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:363
msgid ""
":kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`<` moves to the beginning of the commandline, :kbd:"
"`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`>` moves to the end."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:365
msgid ""
":kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`K` deletes from the cursor to the end of line "
"(moving it to the :ref:`killring`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:367
msgid ""
":kbd:`Escape` and :kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`G` cancel the current "
"operation. Immediately after an unambiguous completion this undoes it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:369
msgid ":kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`C` capitalizes the current word."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:371
msgid ":kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`U` makes the current word uppercase."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:373
msgid ":kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`T` transposes the last two characters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:375
msgid ":kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`T` transposes the last two words."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:377
msgid ""
":kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`Z`, :kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`_` (:kbd:"
"`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`/` on some terminals) undo the most recent edit of the "
"line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:379
msgid ":kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`/` reverts the most recent undo."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:381
msgid ""
":kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`R` opens the history in a pager. This will show "
"history entries matching the search, a few at a time. Pressing :kbd:"
"`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`R` again will search older entries, pressing :kbd:"
"`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`S` (that otherwise toggles pager search) will go to "
"newer entries. The search bar will always be selected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:384
msgid ""
"You can change these key bindings using the :doc:`bind <cmds/bind>` builtin."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:390
msgid "Vi mode commands"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:392
msgid ""
"Vi mode allows for the use of Vi-like commands at the prompt. Initially, :"
"ref:`insert mode <vi-mode-insert>` is active. :kbd:`Escape` enters :ref:"
"`command mode <vi-mode-command>`. The commands available in command, insert "
"and visual mode are described below. Vi mode shares :ref:`some bindings "
"<shared-binds>` with :ref:`Emacs mode <emacs-mode>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:394
msgid ""
"To enable vi mode, use :doc:`fish_vi_key_bindings <cmds/"
"fish_vi_key_bindings>`. It is also possible to add all emacs-mode bindings "
"to vi-mode by using something like::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:398
msgid ""
"function fish_user_key_bindings\n"
"    # Execute this once per mode that emacs bindings should be used in\n"
"    fish_default_key_bindings -M insert\n"
"\n"
"    # Then execute the vi-bindings so they take precedence when there's a "
"conflict.\n"
"    # Without --no-erase fish_vi_key_bindings will default to\n"
"    # resetting all bindings.\n"
"    # The argument specifies the initial mode (insert, \"default\" or "
"visual).\n"
"    fish_vi_key_bindings --no-erase insert\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:410
msgid ""
"When in vi-mode, the :doc:`fish_mode_prompt <cmds/fish_mode_prompt>` "
"function will display a mode indicator to the left of the prompt. To disable "
"this feature, override it with an empty function. To display the mode "
"elsewhere (like in your right prompt), use the output of the "
"``fish_default_mode_prompt`` function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:412
msgid ""
"When a binding switches the mode, it will repaint the mode-prompt if it "
"exists, and the rest of the prompt only if it doesn't. So if you want a mode-"
"indicator in your ``fish_prompt``, you need to erase ``fish_mode_prompt`` e."
"g. by adding an empty file at ``~/.config/fish/functions/fish_mode_prompt."
"fish``. (Bindings that change the mode are supposed to call the `repaint-"
"mode` bind function, see :doc:`bind <cmds/bind>`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:414
msgid ""
"The ``fish_vi_cursor`` function will be used to change the cursor's shape "
"depending on the mode in supported terminals. The following snippet can be "
"used to manually configure cursors after enabling vi-mode::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:416
msgid ""
"# Emulates vim's cursor shape behavior\n"
"# Set the normal and visual mode cursors to a block\n"
"set fish_cursor_default block\n"
"# Set the insert mode cursor to a line\n"
"set fish_cursor_insert line\n"
"# Set the replace mode cursors to an underscore\n"
"set fish_cursor_replace_one underscore\n"
"set fish_cursor_replace underscore\n"
"# Set the external cursor to a line. The external cursor appears when a "
"command is started.\n"
"# The cursor shape takes the value of fish_cursor_default when "
"fish_cursor_external is not specified.\n"
"set fish_cursor_external line\n"
"# The following variable can be used to configure cursor shape in\n"
"# visual mode, but due to fish_cursor_default, is redundant here\n"
"set fish_cursor_visual block"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:431
msgid ""
"Additionally, ``blink`` can be added after each of the cursor shape "
"parameters to set a blinking cursor in the specified shape."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:433
msgid ""
"Fish knows the shapes \"block\", \"line\" and \"underscore\", other values "
"will be ignored."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:435
msgid ""
"If the cursor shape does not appear to be changing after setting the above "
"variables, it's likely your terminal emulator does not support the "
"capabilities necessary to do this. It may also be the case, however, that "
"``fish_vi_cursor`` has not detected your terminal's features correctly (for "
"example, if you are using ``tmux``). If this is the case, you can force "
"``fish_vi_cursor`` to set the cursor shape by setting "
"``$fish_vi_force_cursor`` in ``config.fish``. You'll have to restart fish "
"for any changes to take effect. If cursor shape setting remains broken after "
"this, it's almost certainly an issue with your terminal emulator, and not "
"fish."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:440
msgid "Command mode"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:442
msgid "Command mode is also known as normal mode."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:444 ../../../interactive.rst:501
msgid ":kbd:`h` moves the cursor left."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:446 ../../../interactive.rst:503
msgid ":kbd:`l` moves the cursor right."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:448
msgid ""
":kbd:`k` and :kbd:`j` search the command history for the previous/next "
"command containing the string that was specified on the commandline before "
"the search was started. If the commandline was empty when the search "
"started, all commands match. See the :ref:`history <history-search>` section "
"for more information on history searching. In multi-line commands, they move "
"the cursor up and down respectively."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:450
msgid ""
":kbd:`i` enters :ref:`insert mode <vi-mode-insert>` at the current cursor "
"position."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:452
msgid ""
":kbd:`Shift`\\ +\\ :kbd:`I` enters :ref:`insert mode <vi-mode-insert>` at "
"the beginning of the line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:454
msgid ""
":kbd:`v` enters :ref:`visual mode <vi-mode-visual>` at the current cursor "
"position."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:456
msgid ""
":kbd:`a` enters :ref:`insert mode <vi-mode-insert>` after the current cursor "
"position."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:458
msgid ""
":kbd:`Shift`\\ +\\ :kbd:`A` enters :ref:`insert mode <vi-mode-insert>` at "
"the end of the line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:460
msgid ""
":kbd:`o` inserts a new line under the current one and enters :ref:`insert "
"mode <vi-mode-insert>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:462
msgid ""
":kbd:`O` (capital-\"o\") inserts a new line above the current one and "
"enters :ref:`insert mode <vi-mode-insert>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:464
msgid ""
":kbd:`0` (zero) moves the cursor to beginning of line (remaining in command "
"mode)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:466
msgid ""
":kbd:`d`\\ +\\ :kbd:`d` deletes the current line and moves it to the :ref:"
"`killring`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:468
msgid ""
":kbd:`Shift`\\ +\\ :kbd:`D` deletes text after the current cursor position "
"and moves it to the :ref:`killring`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:470
msgid ":kbd:`p` pastes text from the :ref:`killring`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:472
msgid ":kbd:`u` undoes the most recent edit of the command line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:473
msgid ":kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`R` redoes the most recent edit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:475
msgid ""
":kbd:`[` and :kbd:`]` search the command history for the previous/next token "
"containing the token under the cursor before the search was started. See "
"the :ref:`history <history-search>` section for more information on history "
"searching."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:477
msgid ""
":kbd:`/` opens the history in a pager. This will show history entries "
"matching the search, a few at a time. Pressing it again will search older "
"entries, pressing :kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`S` (that otherwise toggles "
"pager search) will go to newer entries. The search bar will always be "
"selected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:479
msgid ":kbd:`Backspace` moves the cursor left."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:481
msgid ""
":kbd:`g` / :kbd:`G` moves the cursor to the beginning/end of the "
"commandline, respectively."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:483
msgid ":kbd:`:q` exits fish."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:488
msgid "Insert mode"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:490
msgid ":kbd:`Escape` enters :ref:`command mode <vi-mode-command>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:492
msgid ":kbd:`Backspace` removes one character to the left."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:497
msgid "Visual mode"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:499
msgid ""
":kbd:`←` (Left) and :kbd:`→` (Right) extend the selection backward/forward "
"by one character."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:505
msgid ":kbd:`k` moves the cursor up."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:507
msgid ":kbd:`j` moves the cursor down."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:509
msgid ""
":kbd:`b` and :kbd:`w` extend the selection backward/forward by one word."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:511
msgid ""
":kbd:`d` and :kbd:`x` move the selection to the :ref:`killring` and enter :"
"ref:`command mode <vi-mode-command>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:513
msgid ""
":kbd:`Escape` and :kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`C` enter :ref:`command mode <vi-"
"mode-command>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:515
msgid ":kbd:`c` and :kbd:`s` remove the selection and switch to insert mode."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:517
msgid ""
":kbd:`X` moves the entire line to the :ref:`killring`, and enters :ref:"
"`command mode <vi-mode-command>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:519
msgid ""
":kbd:`y` copies the selection to the :ref:`killring`, and enters :ref:"
"`command mode <vi-mode-command>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:521
msgid ""
":kbd:`~` toggles the case (upper/lower) on the selection, and enters :ref:"
"`command mode <vi-mode-command>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:523
msgid ""
":kbd:`\"*y` copies the selection to the clipboard, and enters :ref:`command "
"mode <vi-mode-command>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:528
msgid "Custom bindings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:530
msgid ""
"In addition to the standard bindings listed here, you can also define your "
"own with :doc:`bind <cmds/bind>`::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:532
msgid ""
"# Just clear the commandline on control-c\n"
"bind \\cc 'commandline -r \"\"'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:535
msgid ""
"Put ``bind`` statements into :ref:`config.fish <configuration>` or a "
"function called ``fish_user_key_bindings``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:537
msgid ""
"If you change your mind on a binding and want to go back to fish's default, "
"you can simply erase it again::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:539
msgid "bind --erase \\cc"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:541
msgid ""
"Fish remembers its preset bindings and so it will take effect again. This "
"saves you from having to remember what it was before and add it again "
"yourself."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:543
msgid ""
"If you use :ref:`vi bindings <vi-mode>`, note that ``bind`` will by default "
"bind keys in :ref:`command mode <vi-mode-command>`. To bind something in :"
"ref:`insert mode <vi-mode-insert>`::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:545
msgid "bind --mode insert \\cc 'commandline -r \"\"'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:550
msgid "Key sequences"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:552
msgid ""
"The terminal tells fish which keys you pressed by sending some sequences of "
"bytes to describe that key. For some keys, this is easy - pressing :kbd:`a` "
"simply means the terminal sends \"a\". In others it's more complicated and "
"terminals disagree on which they send."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:554
msgid ""
"In these cases, :doc:`fish_key_reader <cmds/fish_key_reader>` can tell you "
"how to write the key sequence for your terminal. Just start it and press the "
"keys you are interested in::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:556
msgid ""
"> fish_key_reader # pressing control-c\n"
"Press a key:\n"
"Press [ctrl-C] again to exit\n"
"bind \\cC 'do something'\n"
"\n"
"> fish_key_reader # pressing the right-arrow\n"
"Press a key:\n"
"bind \\e\\[C 'do something'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:565
msgid ""
"Note that some key combinations are indistinguishable or unbindable. For "
"instance control-i *is the same* as the tab key. This is a terminal "
"limitation that fish can't do anything about. When ``fish_key_reader`` "
"prints the same sequence for two different keys, then that is because your "
"terminal sends the same sequence for them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:567
msgid ""
"Also, :kbd:`Escape` is the same thing as :kbd:`Alt` in a terminal. To "
"distinguish between pressing :kbd:`Escape` and then another key, and "
"pressing :kbd:`Alt` and that key (or an escape sequence the key sends), fish "
"waits for a certain time after seeing an escape character. This is "
"configurable via the :envvar:`fish_escape_delay_ms` variable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:569
msgid ""
"If you want to be able to press :kbd:`Escape` and then a character and have "
"it count as :kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ that character, set it to a higher value, e.g.::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:571
msgid "set -g fish_escape_delay_ms 100"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:573
msgid ""
"Similarly, to disambiguate *other* keypresses where you've bound a "
"subsequence and a longer sequence, fish has :envvar:"
"`fish_sequence_key_delay_ms`::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:575
msgid ""
"# This binds \"jk\" to switch to normal mode in vi-mode.\n"
"# If you kept it like that, every time you press \"j\",\n"
"# fish would wait for a \"k\" or other key to disambiguate\n"
"bind -M insert -m default jk cancel repaint-mode\n"
"\n"
"# After setting this, fish only waits 200ms for the \"k\",\n"
"# or decides to treat the \"j\" as a separate sequence, inserting it.\n"
"set -g fish_sequence_key_delay_ms 200"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:587
msgid "Copy and paste (Kill Ring)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:589
msgid ""
"Fish uses an Emacs-style kill ring for copy and paste functionality. For "
"example, use :kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`K` (`kill-line`) to cut from the "
"current cursor position to the end of the line. The string that is cut (a.k."
"a. killed in emacs-ese) is inserted into a list of kills, called the kill "
"ring. To paste the latest value from the kill ring (emacs calls this "
"\"yanking\") use :kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`Y` (the ``yank`` input "
"function). After pasting, use :kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`Y` (``yank-pop``) to "
"rotate to the previous kill."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:591
msgid ""
"Copy and paste from outside are also supported, both via the :kbd:"
"`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`X` / :kbd:`Control`\\ +\\ :kbd:`V` bindings (the "
"``fish_clipboard_copy`` and ``fish_clipboard_paste`` functions [#]_) and via "
"the terminal's paste function, for which fish enables \"Bracketed Paste "
"Mode\", so it can tell a paste from manually entered text. In addition, when "
"pasting inside single quotes, pasted single quotes and backslashes are "
"automatically escaped so that the result can be used as a single token "
"simply by closing the quote after. Kill ring entries are stored in "
"``fish_killring`` variable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:595
msgid ""
"The commands ``begin-selection`` and ``end-selection`` (unbound by default; "
"used for selection in vi visual mode) control text selection together with "
"cursor movement commands that extend the current selection. The variable :"
"envvar:`fish_cursor_selection_mode` can be used to configure if that "
"selection should include the character under the cursor (``inclusive``) or "
"not (``exclusive``). The default is ``exclusive``, which works well with any "
"cursor shape. For vi mode, and particularly for the ``block`` or "
"``underscore`` cursor shapes you may prefer ``inclusive``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:598
msgid ""
"These rely on external tools. Currently xsel, xclip, wl-copy/wl-paste and "
"pbcopy/pbpaste are supported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:603
msgid "Multiline editing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:605
msgid ""
"The fish commandline editor can be used to work on commands that are several "
"lines long. There are three ways to make a command span more than a single "
"line:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:607
msgid ""
"Pressing the :kbd:`Enter` key while a block of commands is unclosed, such as "
"when one or more block commands such as ``for``, ``begin`` or ``if`` do not "
"have a corresponding :doc:`end <cmds/end>` command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:609
msgid ""
"Pressing :kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`Enter` instead of pressing the :kbd:`Enter` "
"key."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:611
msgid ""
"By inserting a backslash (``\\``) character before pressing the :kbd:`Enter` "
"key, escaping the newline."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:613
msgid ""
"The fish commandline editor works exactly the same in single line mode and "
"in multiline mode. To move between lines use the left and right arrow keys "
"and other such keyboard shortcuts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:618
msgid "Searchable command history"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:620
msgid ""
"After a command has been executed, it is remembered in the history list. Any "
"duplicate history items are automatically removed. By pressing the up and "
"down keys, you can search forwards and backwards in the history. If the "
"current command line is not empty when starting a history search, only the "
"commands containing the string entered into the command line are shown."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:622
msgid ""
"By pressing :kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`↑` and :kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`↓`, a "
"history search is also performed, but instead of searching for a complete "
"commandline, each commandline is broken into separate elements just like it "
"would be before execution, and the history is searched for an element "
"matching that under the cursor."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:624
msgid ""
"For more complicated searches, you can press :kbd:`Ctrl`\\ +\\ :kbd:`R` to "
"open a pager that allows you to search the history. It shows a limited "
"number of entries in one page, press :kbd:`Ctrl`\\ +\\ :kbd:`R` [#]_ again "
"to move to the next page and :kbd:`Ctrl`\\ +\\ :kbd:`S` [#]_ to move to the "
"previous page. You can change the text to refine your search."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:626
msgid ""
"History searches are case-insensitive unless the search string contains an "
"uppercase character. You can stop a search to edit your search string by "
"pressing :kbd:`Esc` or :kbd:`Page Down`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:628
msgid ""
"Prefixing the commandline with a space will prevent the entire line from "
"being stored in the history. It will still be available for recall until the "
"next command is executed, but will not be stored on disk. This is to allow "
"you to fix misspellings and such."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:630
msgid ""
"The command history is stored in the file ``~/.local/share/fish/"
"fish_history`` (or ``$XDG_DATA_HOME/fish/fish_history`` if that variable is "
"set) by default. However, you can set the ``fish_history`` environment "
"variable to change the name of the history session (resulting in a "
"``<session>_history`` file); both before starting the shell and while the "
"shell is running."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:635
msgid "See the :doc:`history <cmds/history>` command for other manipulations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:639
msgid ""
"To search for previous entries containing the word 'make', type ``make`` in "
"the console and press the up key."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:641
msgid ""
"If the commandline reads ``cd m``, place the cursor over the ``m`` character "
"and press :kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`↑` to search for previously typed words "
"containing 'm'."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:643
msgid ""
"Or another binding that triggers the ``history-pager`` input function. See :"
"doc:`bind <cmds/bind>` for a list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:644
msgid ""
"Or another binding that triggers the ``pager-toggle-search`` input function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:647
msgid "Navigating directories"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:651
msgid ""
"Navigating directories is usually done with the :doc:`cd <cmds/cd>` command, "
"but fish offers some advanced features as well."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:653
msgid ""
"The current working directory can be displayed with the :doc:`pwd <cmds/"
"pwd>` command, or the ``$PWD`` :ref:`special variable <variables-special>`. "
"Usually your prompt already does this."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:656
msgid "Directory history"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:658
msgid ""
"Fish automatically keeps a trail of the recent visited directories with :doc:"
"`cd <cmds/cd>` by storing this history in the ``dirprev`` and ``dirnext`` "
"variables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:660
msgid "Several commands are provided to interact with this directory history:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:662
msgid ":doc:`dirh <cmds/dirh>` prints the history"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:663
msgid ":doc:`cdh <cmds/cdh>` displays a prompt to quickly navigate the history"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:664
msgid ""
":doc:`prevd <cmds/prevd>` moves backward through the history. It is bound "
"to :kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`←`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:665
msgid ""
":doc:`nextd <cmds/nextd>` moves forward through the history. It is bound to :"
"kbd:`Alt`\\ +\\ :kbd:`→`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:670
msgid "Directory stack"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:672
msgid ""
"Another set of commands, usually also available in other shells like bash, "
"deal with the directory stack. Stack handling is not automatic and needs "
"explicit calls of the following commands:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:674
msgid ":doc:`dirs <cmds/dirs>` prints the stack"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:675
msgid ""
":doc:`pushd <cmds/pushd>` adds a directory on top of the stack and makes it "
"the current working directory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../interactive.rst:676
msgid ""
":doc:`popd <cmds/popd>` removes the directory on top of the stack and "
"changes the current working directory"
msgstr ""
